Exercise 6 instructions.

Download the data âPSE_MOL_Doors.savâ, these are the data from an experiment by Kamila Irvine and Piers Cornelissen. This file contains data on 95 women performing various scales and body image-related tasks. doors_front is the score from a gap estimation task, w_dn is the actual gap a participant can pass through. The (estimated) Point of subjective equality or PSE (the BMI they believe themselves to be) when viewing an imageset varying in BMI. Participants used the method of adjustment to estimate their body size with the same stimulus set as for the yes-no task (MOL). BMI is the participantâs actual BMI.

Test the mediation model: doors_front â> PSE â> BMI via the causal steps method by Baron & Kenny. Report as you would do in a paper.

Make a diagram (use âmediateâ).

Calculate a Sobel z test and report.

Test the mediation via Preacher & Hayes method.

Now test a mediation model with 2 mediators (PSE and MOL) but with the same independent and dependent variables.

Export a figure for that mediation model.

Test the mediation via Imai et al.âs method.

BONUS: perform the sensitivity analysis via Imai et al.âs method.

library(diagram)

                name= c( "PSE","Doors", "BMI"), 
                box.type = "rect", box.size = 0.12, box.prop=0.5,  curve=0)

Note that âmediateâ will standardize coefficients, which is why they are different from the above graph. (You can replace the values from the above as it is a better figure)

require(psych)
## Loading required package: psych
mediationmodel1<-mediate("BMI","doors_front", m=c("PSE"), std=TRUE, data=Data, n.iter=10000, plot=F)
mediate.diagram(mediationmodel1)

Summary: A mediation analysis via Baron & Kennyâs (1986) method showed that there was mediation (Figure X).

Sobel z test.

The mediator contains missing values! Therefore we remove thoseâ¦ .

# create reduced dataframe. Remove missings.
Data_red<-na.omit(cbind.data.frame(Data$PSE,Data$doors_front,Data$BMI))
# rename the columns.
colnames(Data_red)<-c("PSE","doors","BMI")
require(bda)
## Loading required package: bda
mediation.test(Data_red$PSE,Data_red$doors, Data_red$BMI)
##                Sobel       Aroian      Goodman
## z.value 3.6317053592 3.6165813558 3.6470207025
## p.value 0.0002815545 0.0002985195 0.0002652986

A Sobel z test showed that the mediation effect reported in Fig. X was significant (Sobel z= 3.63, p=.0003).

Preacher & Hayes method.

Standardized indirect effects were computed for 10,000 bootstrapped samples, and the 95% percentile confidence interval was examined via the âpsychâ package. The bootstrapped standardized indirect effect was 0.27, and the 95% confidence interval ranged from 0.12 to 0.41. Thus, the indirect effect was statistically significant and mediation is supported.

require(psych)
mediate("BMI","doors_front",m=c("PSE"), std=T, data= Data, n.iter=10000)

Both PSE and MOL.

Note that this averages the effect of the mediators.

Mediate. (+ Bonus: sensitivity analysis)

The âmediateâ function cannot handle multiple mediators, we therefore test them sequentially. âmultimedâ can handle multiple mediators but cannot take continuous variables as âtreatâ.

Important: below will take time.

require(mediation)
## Loading required package: mediation
## Loading required package: MASS
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loading required package: mvtnorm
## Loading required package: sandwich
## mediation: Causal Mediation Analysis
## Version: 4.4.6
## 
## Attaching package: 'mediation'
## The following object is masked from 'package:psych':
## 
##     mediate
med.fit<-lm(PSE~doors_front, data=Data)
out.fit<-lm(BMI~doors_front+PSE, data=Data)
# Robust SE is ignored for Bootstrap. Otherwise omit boot=TRUE.
set.seed(1984)
med.out <- mediate(med.fit, out.fit, treat = "doors_front", mediator = "PSE", boot=TRUE, sims = 10000)
summary(med.out)
## 
## Causal Mediation Analysis 
## 
## Nonparametric Bootstrap Confidence Intervals with the Percentile Method
## 
##                Estimate 95% CI Lower 95% CI Upper p-value    
## ACME             0.1359       0.0589         0.21  0.0010 ***
## ADE              0.0195      -0.0633         0.10  0.6420    
## Total Effect     0.1555       0.0559         0.25  0.0038 ** 
## Prop. Mediated   0.8744       0.4697         1.81  0.0040 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Sample Size Used: 95 
## 
## 
## Simulations: 10000
plot(med.out) 

sensitivity_analysis<-medsens(med.out) 
## Note: method with signature 'matrix#sparseMatrix' chosen for function '%*%',
##  target signature 'matrix#dgTMatrix'.
##  "ANY#TsparseMatrix" would also be valid

##  target signature 'matrix#dtTMatrix'.

summary(sensitivity_analysis)

## R^2_M*R^2_Y* at which ACME = 0: 0.49

Using a 1,000 bootstraps, the mediation analysis via Imai, Keele & Tingleyâs method (2011) showed a significant average causal mediation effect (ACME): 0.14, 95%CI [0.06, 0.21]. However, the average direct effect was no longer significant (ADE):.02, 95%CI [-0.06, 0.10].

Now we do the same via MOL.

require(mediation)
med.fit2<-lm(MOL~doors_front, data=Data)
out.fit2<-lm(BMI~doors_front+MOL, data=Data)
# Robust SE is ignored for Bootstrap. Otherwise omit boot=TRUE.
set.seed(1984)
med.out2 <- mediate(med.fit2, out.fit2, treat = "doors_front", mediator = "MOL", boot=TRUE, sims = 10000)

So, we find support for mediation via both paths. The âhidden confounderâ has to be stronger for MOL than for PSE in order to explain away the mediation effect.
